Results.
The results on FB15k-237-C3, C5 and C10 are presented in Table1, and those on FB15k-237-R3, R5 and R10 are shown in AppendixC.1.
We can find that (i) our proposed FedLU can generally achieve better performance in link prediction than others.
(ii) For different client numbers, FedLU achieves consistent performance after convergence.
As shown in Figure4 shortly, the convergence round becomes larger with the number of clients increases.
(iii) Compared to the independent setting, FedProx, FedEC and FedLU all gain improvement, while the results of FedE do not significantly increase or even decline sometimes.
This indicates that FedE can hardly handle such heterogeneous datasets.
(iv) We also see that, in several cases, FedLU even outperforms the centralized setting, suggesting that for the datasets with strong heterogeneity, smoothly exchanging knowledge through mutual distillation is more appropriate than directly sharing data.
(v) In most cases, FedLU (global) achieves the second-best performance, which is only behind FedLU (local).
This shows that FedLU obtains a global entity embedding which is compatible with local embeddings in clients.

Compared with the results in Table1, we also find two interesting differences.
First, the gap between the independent setting and the centralized setting is more significant.
This is because FB15k-237-R3/R5/R10 are less heterogeneous, which are easier to obtain noticeable increases with more data.
Second, FedLU (local) generally underperforms FedLU (global) in Table4, while it performs better in Table1.
The global embedding stored in FedLU represents the characteristics of the entire data.
They cannot capture the local heterogeneous data on each client well.
FB15k-237-R3/R5/R10 do not encounter such an issue as they are nearly homogeneous.

Results.
The unlearning results on the FB15k-237-C3 dataset are shown in Table2, and other results are given in Appendix C.2.
We have three findings:
(i) The Hits@1 and MRR scores of the re-trained models on the forgetting sets are close to those on the test sets.
This indicates that the re-trained models are still able to predict missing links, i.e., completely forgetting cannot be achieved through re-training from scratch.
(ii) The scores of the unlearned embeddings drop to a lower level on the forgetting sets than the raw embeddings and the re-trained embeddings, suggesting that FedLU is able to erase the knowledge thoroughly and suppress the activation of the memory to the forgetting sets during unlearning.
(iii) The unlearned embeddings achieve comparable performance on the test sets with the raw models, which is higher than the re-trained models.
This indicates that unlearning in FedLU can maintain the global knowledge absorbed in FL.

To evaluate the effectiveness of the hard and soft confusions in the retroactive interference step of FedLU, we modify two variants in federated unlearning, namely FedLU without hard confusion and FedLU without soft confusion.
From Table3, we find that:
(i) The Hits@1 scores of FedLU without hard or soft confusion on the forgetting sets are much lower than those of the raw models in Table2, suggesting that both of them are effective.
(ii) FedLU without hard confusion shows higher Hits@1 on the forgetting sets, indicating that the hard confusion plays a key role in unlearning.
(iii) The Hits@1 scores of FedLU without soft confusion is slightly higher than the original FedLU.
This shows that the soft confusion acts as a fine-tuning factor in retroactive inference.

We also conduct federated unlearning on FB15k-237-C5 and FB15k-237-C10.
Tables5 and 6 show the average results.
The conclusion is similar to that from Table2.
Compared with the raw results, the results on the forgetting sets decrease rapidly with our unlearning method, while there are only slight declines on the test sets.
We also notice that the re-trained results on the forgetting sets are much higher than our unlearning results.
This not only indicates that simply re-training on the retaining sets cannot achieve unlearning, but also validates that our proposed unlearning method is effective.
